Back when I was maintaining Accerciser, my technique was to check the versions of IPython that the last upstream distros were using (or were going to use). This involved checking what was in Debian testing (what Ubuntu "usually" takes for the upcoming release), Fedora, openSUSE and Arch.

This way, I could know the versions that Accerciser's IPython plugin had to support at a specific moment. Bear in mind that IPython is not a "real" GNOME dependency, so we need to deal with its support ourselves.

DLang also has tools for:
1. [Linting (DScanner)](https://github.com/dlang-community/D-Scanner)
2. [Auto Completion (DCD)](https://github.com/dlang-community/DCD)
3. [Unit Tests (via DUB)](https://github.com/dlang/dub)

Unit tests are inlined in the code you write via the unittest keyword.
```d
int getValue() {
    return 42;
}

unittest {
    assert(getValue==42, "Value was unexpected!");
}
```

